choices.text: with a bottle of water and a machete. I started out by scaling a rope ladder that was made from climbing vines into a house full of dingy, sparring farmers. I was told by Corey, who was delicately clawing coconut meat out of a fruit by pounding the crab-cakes footprint into the shell with a hammer, that before I resinated down the next stairs of the house I needed to don a leather machete belt. This machete belt is so that if I happen to trip on the recurring dirt steps and fall and somehow end up running through the house instead of walking, there’s a good chance that I will ram my machete into everyone’s groin right before I land, potentially knocking out one or more of the farmers. After adjusting my belt that was made from recycled motorcycle inner tubes, he instructed me to “grab the coconut”. Without the use of anything else- it’s a nice way of saying that the main things the guests will see on a Guyanese grocery mission are the entire spice room lined with crates of live chickens, pigs, and chicken intestine and bile. It should look like a carnivorous factory, complete with butchered refrigerators and packaging machines that all look and move like tors climbed out of an Anime. Today’s crop was live chicken. Not like regular chickens. These chickens have been called a lot of things. Most of these names are unmentionable because “chicken” comes roughly 10 millimetres after “cock”.
